04646nam a22006015i 9780292744226DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927442267 a10.7560/7442192doi  a(DE-B1597)586816  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN1998.3.S593bG36 2013eb 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4302/330922231 aGallagher, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnother Steven Soderbergh Experience :bAuthorship and Contemporary Hollywood /cMark Gallagher. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One Soderbergh and American Cinema -- tChapter 1 Sex, Lies, and Independent Film -- tChapter 2 Hollywood Authorship and Transhistorical Taste Cultures -- tPart Two Authoring and Authorization -- tChapter 3 Authorial Practice, Collaboration, and Location Production -- tChapter 4 Critical Reception and the Soderbergh Imprint -- tPart Three Soderbergh and Textuality -- tChapter 5 Reading Soderbergh Textuality and Representation -- tChapter 6 Intertextual Conversations Genre, Adaptations, and Remakes -- tPart Four Soderbergh and Screen Industries -- tChapter 7 Soderbergh and Television -- tChapter 8 Boutique Cinema, Section Eight, and DVD -- tConclusion -- tAppendix Interview with Steven Soderbergh New York City, Saturday, July 23, 2011 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do we determine authorship in film, and what happens when we look in-depth at the creative activity of living filmmakers rather than approach their work through the abstract prism of auteur theory? Mark Gallagher uses Steven Soderbergh’s career as a lens through which to re-view screen authorship and offer a new model that acknowledges the fundamentally collaborative nature of authorial work and its circulation. Working in film, television, and digital video, Soderbergh is the most prolific and protean filmmaker in contemporary American cinema. At the same time, his activity typifies contemporary screen industry practice, in which production entities, distribution platforms, and creative labor increasingly cross-pollinate. Gallagher investigates Soderbergh’s work on such films as The Limey, Erin Brockovich, Ocean’s Eleven and its sequels, Solaris, The Good German, Che, and The Informant!, as well as on the K Street television series. Dispensing with classical auteurist models, he positions Soderbergh and authorship in terms of collaborative production, location filming activity, dealmaking and distribution, textual representation, genre and adaptation work, critical reception, and other industrial and cultural phenomena. Gallagher also addresses Soderbergh’s role as standard-bearer for U.S. independent cinema following 1989’s sex, lies and videotape, as well as his cinephilic dialogues with different forms of U.S. and international cinema from the 1920s through the 1970s. Including an extensive new interview with the filmmaker, Another Steven Soderbergh Experience demonstrates how industries and institutions cultivate, recognize, and challenge creative screen artists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292744226423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292744226/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles 